    Raising roofs, crashing cycles, and playing pool: applications of
a data structure for finding pairwise interactions . 
D. Eppstein and 
 J. Erickson .  
 14th ACM Symp. Comp. Geom.,  Minneapolis, 1998, pp. 58–67 .  Disc. Comp. Geom.  22 (4): 569–592, 1999 (special issue for SCG 1998).
 
We use my dynamic closest pair data structure
from " Dynamic Euclidean minimum
spanning trees " to detect collisions among a collection of moving
objects in sublinear time per collision.  As one application, we can
construct the  straight skeleton  of Aichholzer et al (and the mitered
offset curves from which it is defined) in subquadratic time.
